A process P has PID 5000.
Step 1
Process starts.
PID = 5000
It prints:
Before fork: parent PID = 5000
Output so far:
Before fork: parent PID = 5000
Step 2
Program executes:
fork();
fork() creates a new child process.
Now there are 2 processes:
Parent PID = 5000
Child  PID = 5001
(The question already says kernel assigned PID 5001 to child.)
Step 3
Return value of fork()
In Parent
pid = fork();
returns child's PID.
So parent gets:
pid = 5001
Parent prints:
Parent: my PID = 5000, child PID = 5001
In Child
fork() returns:
0
Child prints:
Child: my PID = 5001, parent PID = 5000
Step 4
After fork, parent and child run concurrently.
The scheduler may run:
•	Parent first 
•	Child first 
So order is not guaranteed.
Case 1 : Parent runs first
Before fork: parent PID = 5000
Parent: my PID = 5000, child PID = 5001
Child: my PID = 5001, parent PID = 5000
Case 2 : Child runs first
Before fork: parent PID = 5000
Child: my PID = 5001, parent PID = 5000
Parent: my PID = 5000, child PID = 5001
First line always first
Because it is printed before fork().
Only one process exists then.
So:
Before fork: parent PID = 5000
must appear first.
wait(NULL)
Parent executes:
wait(NULL);
Meaning:
Parent waits until child finishes.
It prevents the child from becoming a zombie process.
But it does not force the parent's print statement to come after the child's print statement because the parent prints before calling wait().

